oc:kn_0351a39a a oc:KnowledgeNode,
        oc:OutputFormat ;
    oc:directiveContent """## Outputs
1. **Competitor Data File**: YAML profile per competitor
2. **Page Content**: URL, meta tags, full page copy by section, comparison tables, CTAs
3. **Page Set Plan**: Recommended pages prioritized by search volume""" ;
    oc:templateVariables "Competitor Data File",
        "Page Content",
        "Page Set Plan" .

oc:kn_2653b2a0 a oc:KnowledgeNode,
        oc:WorkflowStrategy ;
    oc:appliesToContext "When beginning competitor research for any new competitor" ;
    oc:directiveContent "For each competitor, research five dimensions: (1) product hands-on use, (2) pricing including hidden costs, (3) review mining from G2/Capterra/TrustRadius, (4) customer switch feedback both directions, (5) competitor's own positioning and comparison pages." ;
    oc:hasRationale "Multi-source research produces accurate, defensible comparisons that hold up under reader scrutiny." ;
    oc:severityLevel "MEDIUM" .

oc:kn_34ed25cb a oc:DesignPrinciple,
        oc:KnowledgeNode ;
    oc:appliesToContext "When building more than one comparison page" ;
    oc:directiveContent "Use a centralized competitor data architecture with a single YAML file per competitor as the source of truth. Each comparison page pulls from these centralized files so updates propagate everywhere." ;
    oc:hasRationale "Centralized data prevents inconsistency across pages and reduces maintenance burden when competitor pricing or features change." ;
    oc:severityLevel "HIGH" .

oc:kn_35f1874f a oc:KnowledgeNode,
        oc:Procedure ;
    oc:appliesToContext "When creating any competitor comparison page" ;
    oc:directiveContent "1. Check for product-marketing-context.md and read it. 2. Identify which of the 4 page formats matches the request (singular alternative, plural alternatives, you vs competitor, competitor vs competitor). 3. Gather competitor data using the centralized YAML structure. 4. Generate page content following format-specific structure. 5. Add SEO optimization (keywords, schema markup, internal links). 6. Output competitor data file + page content + page set plan." ;
    oc:stepOrder 1 .

oc:kn_3acb62af a oc:KnowledgeNode,
        oc:RecoveryTactic ;
    oc:appliesToContext "When user mentions 'battle card,' 'objection handling,' or internal sales materials" ;
    oc:directiveContent "If the user requests a battle card or internal sales competitive doc, recognize this as sales-enablement territory and defer to that skill rather than creating public comparison page content." ;
    oc:hasRationale "Internal sales collateral has different requirements (confidential positioning, trap-setting) than public SEO pages." ;
    oc:severityLevel "MEDIUM" .

oc:kn_789b26f3 a oc:KnowledgeNode,
        oc:Procedure ;
    oc:appliesToContext "When creating [Competitor A] vs [Competitor B] pages" ;
    oc:directiveContent "Competitor vs Competitor format: 1. Overview of both products → 2. Comparison by category → 3. Who each is best for → 4. The third option (introduce your product) → 5. Comparison table (all three) → 6. CTA. URL: /compare/[a]-vs-[b]" ;
    oc:stepOrder 5 .

oc:kn_87f4d398 a oc:Heuristic,
        oc:KnowledgeNode ;
    oc:appliesToContext "At the start of every competitor page task" ;
    oc:directiveContent "Check for product-marketing-context.md (.agents/ or .claude/) before asking questions. Use existing context and only ask for uncovered or task-specific information." ;
    oc:hasRationale "Avoids redundant questions and leverages already-documented product knowledge for consistent positioning." ;
    oc:severityLevel "MEDIUM" .

oc:kn_8bc30ba4 a oc:KnowledgeNode,
        oc:Procedure ;
    oc:appliesToContext "When creating You vs [Competitor] pages" ;
    oc:directiveContent "You vs Competitor format: 1. TL;DR summary (2-3 sentences) → 2. At-a-glance comparison table → 3. Detailed comparison by category → 4. Who [You] is best for → 5. Who [Competitor] is best for (honest) → 6. Customer testimonials from switchers → 7. Migration support → 8. CTA. URL: /vs/[competitor] or /compare/[you]-vs-[competitor]" ;
    oc:stepOrder 4 .

oc:kn_a1a97a2d a oc:KnowledgeNode,
        oc:Procedure ;
    oc:appliesToContext "When creating [Competitor] Alternative (singular) pages" ;
    oc:directiveContent "Singular alternative format: 1. Why people look for alternatives → 2. Summary: You as the alternative → 3. Detailed comparison (features, service, pricing) → 4. Who should switch (and who shouldn't) → 5. Migration path → 6. Social proof from switchers → 7. CTA. URL: /alternatives/[competitor]" ;
    oc:stepOrder 2 .

oc:kn_a2010e43 a oc:KnowledgeNode,
        oc:PreFlightCheck ;
    oc:appliesToContext "Before writing any competitor comparison page" ;
    oc:directiveContent "Before creating comparison pages, confirm: your product's core value proposition, key differentiators, ideal customer profile, pricing model, strengths and honest weaknesses, plus the competitive landscape and search volume for competitor terms." ;
    oc:hasRationale "Incomplete product knowledge leads to weak positioning and missed differentiation opportunities." ;
    oc:severityLevel "HIGH" .

oc:kn_adc7a7c7 a oc:CodePattern,
        oc:KnowledgeNode ;
    oc:appliesToContext "When creating competitor data files" ;
    oc:codeLanguage "yaml" ;
    oc:directiveContent """name: [Competitor]
website: [url]
tagline: "[one-liner]"
founded: [year]
pricing_model: [per-seat|flat|usage]
free_tier: [true|false]
starter_price: $X/user/month
features:
  [category]: [1-5 rating]
strengths:
  - [honest strength]
weaknesses:
  - [honest weakness]
best_for:
  - [ideal use case]
not_ideal_for:
  - [limitation scenario]
common_complaints:
  - "[from reviews]"
migration_from:
  difficulty: [easy|medium|hard]
  data_export: "[formats]"
  what_transfers: "[list]"
  what_doesnt: "[list]\"""" .

oc:kn_c2272089 a oc:KnowledgeNode,
        oc:Standard ;
    oc:appliesToContext "When writing any competitor comparison content" ;
    oc:directiveContent "Always acknowledge competitor strengths and be accurate about your own limitations. Never misrepresent competitor features — readers are actively comparing and will verify claims." ;
    oc:hasRationale "Honesty builds trust with evaluators who are cross-referencing claims; dishonesty destroys credibility permanently." ;
    oc:severityLevel "CRITICAL" .

oc:kn_ec76bf45 a oc:Constraint,
        oc:KnowledgeNode ;
    oc:appliesToContext "When creating [Competitor] Alternatives (plural) format pages" ;
    oc:directiveContent "Plural alternatives pages must include 4-7 real alternatives (not just your product). Being genuinely helpful with real options builds trust and ranks better." ;
    oc:hasRationale "SEO rewards comprehensive content; users trust pages that acknowledge real alternatives rather than being purely promotional." ;
    oc:severityLevel "HIGH" .

oc:kn_f3fe72e9 a oc:AntiPattern,
        oc:KnowledgeNode ;
    oc:appliesToContext "When creating feature comparison tables" ;
    oc:directiveContent "Never use simple checkmark/cross tables for feature comparisons. Replace with descriptive cells that explain capability depth and limitations." ;
    oc:hasRationale "Checkmark tables are superficial and don't help readers understand real differences; descriptive comparisons demonstrate expertise and provide genuine value." ;
    oc:severityLevel "HIGH" .

oc:kn_f5f94491 a oc:KnowledgeNode,
        oc:Procedure ;
    oc:appliesToContext "When creating [Competitor] Alternatives (plural) pages" ;
    oc:directiveContent "Plural alternatives format: 1. Why people look for alternatives → 2. What to look for in an alternative (criteria framework) → 3. List of alternatives (you first, include 4-7 real options) → 4. Comparison table → 5. Detailed breakdown of each → 6. Recommendation by use case → 7. CTA. URL: /alternatives/[competitor]-alternatives" ;
    oc:stepOrder 3 .

